Frame Sniper Protocol × 4D Frogman Doctrine

A dual-mode operator model:
	•	Sniper = precision in visible exchanges (words, frames, moments)
	•	Frogman (4D) = unseen positioning across time, context, and perception

One handles the shot.
The other handles the terrain before the shot ever exists.

⸻

I. The Split

Frame Sniper (Surface Layer — T=0)

Operates in the moment.
	•	Identifies frames instantly
	•	Slows tempo
	•	Repositions meaning
	•	Fires clean, minimal responses

Goal: Win the exchange

⸻

4D Frogman (Temporal Layer — T=-1 → T+1)

Operates before, during, and after.
	•	Shapes expectations before interaction
	•	Controls context and narrative drift
	•	Sets traps without announcing them
	•	Leaves ambiguity where useful

Goal: Win the environment the exchange happens in

⸻

II. The Core Insight

Most people try to become better snipers.

But the real leverage is:

If the Frogman did his job, the Sniper barely has to fire.

⸻

III. The 4D Frogman Axes

The Frogman moves in four dimensions:

1. Time
	•	Preload expectations
	•	Delay when needed
	•	Let others overextend

Example:
Say less early → others define themselves → you respond later with clarity

⸻

2. Context
	•	Choose the battlefield
	•	Public vs private
	•	Serious vs playful

Example:
Correct someone privately → you gain alliance
Correct publicly → you gain dominance (but create resistance)

⸻

3. Narrative Drift
	•	Let small assumptions build over time
	•	Guide how others interpret your actions

Example:
Consistently calm → later silence reads as confidence, not weakness

⸻

4. Perception Geometry
	•	What people think is happening vs what is actually happening

Example:
Appear reactive while actually steering
or appear passive while accumulating leverage

⸻

IV. The Sniper Kit (When You Engage)

When the moment comes, you switch to Sniper mode.

1. The Lock

Identify the frame in one sentence:

“This only works if X is true.”

⸻

2. The Breath

Pause. Always.

Tempo = control

⸻

3. The Shot Types

A. Clean Kill (Author Frame)

Replace their frame entirely.

“That assumes speed equals correctness. It doesn’t.”

⸻

B. Mirror Shot (Expose Frame)

Reflect their assumption back at them.

“You’re calling that weakness because you equate restraint with fear.”

⸻

C. Null Shot (Dissolve Frame)

Remove the premise.

“That’s not a valid standard to begin with.”

⸻

D. Ghost Shot (Non-Engagement)

Say less or nothing.

Silence forces them to expand → they reveal more

⸻

V. The Frogman → Sniper Pipeline

This is where it becomes powerful.

Step 1 — Frogman Seeds

Before interaction:
	•	establish tone (calm, sharp, playful, etc.)
	•	create consistent signals
	•	let others form expectations

⸻

Step 2 — Let Them Frame Themselves

People will:
	•	overstate
	•	assume
	•	project

Do not interrupt this too early.

⸻

Step 3 — Sniper Activation

When they commit to a frame:

You:
	•	identify the weak invariant
	•	respond once, precisely

⸻

Step 4 — Return to Water

Do not over-engage.
	•	No rambling
	•	No emotional spill
	•	Let your shot echo

⸻

